POST – Creating Data
POST creates new data.
Example:
You register a new account.
Fill Registration Form

↓

POST Request

↓

Server Saves User

↓

User Created
Example:
fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts", {
    method: "POST",
    headers: {
        "Content-Type": "application/json"
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
        title: "Learning JavaScript",
        body: "Callbacks are awesome!",
        userId: 1
    })
})
.then(function(response) {
    return response.json();
})
.then(function(data) {
    console.log(data);
});
Notice two new things:
method: "POST"
and
body: JSON.stringify(...)
We'll explain JSON.stringify() shortly.
Why Do We Use JSON.stringify()?
JavaScript objects cannot be sent directly over HTTP.
Example:
{
    name: "Adi",
    age: 25
}
The server expects text.
So JavaScript converts the object into JSON text.
Example:
JSON.stringify({
    name: "Adi",
    age: 25
});
Result:
{
    "name": "Adi",
    "age": 25
}
Think of it like putting a letter into an envelope before mailing it.
PUT – Replacing Data
PUT replaces an entire resource.
Suppose the server has:
{
    id: 1,
    name: "John",
    age: 20
}
You send:
{
    name: "Peter",
    age: 25
}
The old data becomes:
{
    name: "Peter",
    age: 25
}
Everything is replaced.
Example:
fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/1", {
    method: "PUT",
    headers: {
        "Content-Type": "application/json"
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
        id: 1,
        title: "Updated Title",
        body: "Updated Content",
        userId: 1
    })
});
PATCH – Updating Part of the Data
PATCH updates only selected fields.
Suppose we have:
{
    name: "John",
    age: 20,
    city: "Nairobi"
}
You only want to change the city.
{
    city: "Mombasa"
}
Everything else stays the same.
Example:
fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/1", {
    method: "PATCH",
    headers: {
        "Content-Type": "application/json"
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
        title: "New Title"
    })
});
Only the title changes.
PUT vs PATCH
Imagine updating a student record.
Original:
{
    name: "Alice",
    age: 21,
    course: "Computer Science"
}
Using PUT:
{
    name: "Alice",
    age: 22,
    course: "Software Engineering"
}
The entire record is replaced.
Using PATCH:
{
    age: 22
}
Only the age changes.
