Common Beginner Mistakes
Mistake 1
Using GET to create data.
Wrong.
GET should only read data.
Mistake 2
Forgetting the request body in POST.
Wrong:
fetch(url, {
    method: "POST"
});
Usually, POST requests need data to send.
Mistake 3
Forgetting Content-Type.
Correct:
headers: {
    "Content-Type": "application/json"
}
This tells the server that you're sending JSON.
Mistake 4
Confusing PUT and PATCH.
Remember:
PUT replaces everything.
PATCH updates only selected fields.
Summary
Today you learned:
HTTP Methods tell the server what action to perform.
GET reads data.
POST creates data.
PUT replaces existing data.
PATCH updates part of existing data.
DELETE removes data.
CRUD maps directly to these HTTP methods.
JSON.stringify() converts JavaScript objects into JSON text before sending them to the server.
